    <item>
      <title>*STAT154——what really becomes &#34;my thing&#34;</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/stat154/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 30 May 2026 20:20:00 &#43;0800</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/stat154/</guid>
      <description><p>When asked about what courses do I like most in Berkeley, I definitely answered STAT154, Statistical Machine Learning, without second thought.</p>
<p>It forms me a fundamental perspective on statistics, since it&rsquo;s also the first time I stepped into the world of statistics.</p>
<p>What kind of perspective?</p>
<p>Statisticians think really different from mathematicians and computer scientists.</p>
<p>Why?</p>
<ul>
<li>We math talks about exact things all the time, there seems always to be some &ldquo;truth&rdquo;, function A can control the increases in function B hence integrability of A ensures integrability of B. However, we talked about real world things in statistics: there&rsquo;s no such thing as &ldquo;real function $y=f(x)$&rdquo;, all we can do is to choose an acceptable one——in what sense? How to tradeoff between two metrics? How to get lower cost plus better performance?</li>
</ul></description>
    </item>
    
